'''St George's Church, Chorley''', is located in St George's Street, [[Chorley]], [[Lancashire]], England.  It is an active [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] [[parish church]] in the deanery of Chorley, the archdeaconry of Blackburn, and the [[diocese of Blackburn]].<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.achurchnearyou.com/chorley-st-george/| title = St George, Chorley| accessdate = 13&nbsp;December 2011| publisher = [[Church of England]]}}</ref>  The church has been designated by [[English Heritage]] as a Grade&nbsp;II* [[listed building]].<ref name=nhl>{{NHLE |num= 1072441|desc= Church of St George, Chorley|accessdate= 13&nbsp;December 2011}}</ref>  It was a [[Commissioners' church]], having received a grant towards its construction from the Church Building Commission.<ref name=port>{{Citation | last = Port| first = M. H.| author-link = | publication-date = | date = | year = 2006| title = 600 New Churches: The Church Building Commission 1818-1856 | edition = 2nd| volume = | series = | publication-place = Reading| place = | publisher = Spire Books| pages = | page = 326| id = | isbn = 978-1-904965-08-4| doi = | oclc = | url = | accessdate =}}</ref>

==History==

The church was built between 1822 and 1825 to a design by [[Thomas Rickman]].<ref name=pev>{{Citation | last =Hartwell| first =Clare| authorlink = | last2 = Pevsner | first2 = Nikolaus | author2-link =Nikolaus Pevsner| series= The Buildings of England| title =Lancashire: North |edition= | publisher =[[Yale University Press]] | year =2009 | origyear=1969 | location = New Haven and London| pages = 214<U+2013>215| url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-300-12667-9}}</ref>  A grant of <U+00A3>12,387 (<U+00A3>{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|12387|1825|{{CURRENTYEAR}}|r=-4}}}} as of {{CURRENTYEAR}}){{Inflation-fn|UK}} was given towards its construction by the Church Building Commission.<ref name=port/>  It was originally a [[chapel of ease]] to the mother church of [[St Laurence's Church, Chorley|St&nbsp;Laurence]], and became a separate parish in 1856.  Later three more parishes were created within its boundaries, St&nbsp;Peter, which had earlier been a district within the parish, St&nbsp;James in 1879, and All Saints in the 1950s.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.stgeorgechorley.co.uk/history.html| title = History| accessdate = 13&nbsp;December 2011| publisher = The Parish Church of St George, Chorley}}</ref>

==Architecture==
===Exterior===
St George's is constructed in [[ashlar]] stone with a [[slate]] roof.  Its architectural style is [[English Gothic architecture#Early English Gothic|Early English]].  The plan consists of a [[nave]] and [[chancel]] in one cell with a [[clerestory]], north and south [[aisle]]s, and a west tower.  The tower is in four stages with angle [[buttress]]es rising to octagonal [[pinnacle]]s.  It has a west doorway under a [[crocket]]ed [[gable]] above which is a tall [[lancet window]].  In three sides of the third stage are clock faces.  In the top stage are [[arcade (architecture)|arcades]] of tall lancets, the outer ones being blind.  The [[parapet]] is [[battlement|embattled]].  The nave and aisles are in seven [[bay (architecture)|bays]].  The bays of the aisles are separated by buttresses rising to pinnacles, and each bay contains a pair of lancet windows. Each bay of the clerestory also contains a pair of lancets.  The east window consists of five stepped lancets.<ref name=nhl/> 

===Interior===
Inside the church the arcades are carried on eight thin [[pier (architecture)|piers]].  There are galleries on three sides carried on [[cast iron]] pillars, their fronts being decorated with [[tracery]].  The ceiling is flat, carried on cast iron, decorated [[hammerbeam roof|hammerbeams]].<ref name=pev/>  At the west end of the north aisle is a [[baptistry]] containing a white [[marble]] [[baptismal font|font]] consisting of an angel carrying a scalloped bowl.  The octagonal sculpted [[pulpit]] was made by Thomas Rawcliffe of Chorley.<ref name=nhl/>  The eagle [[lectern]] is a memorial to the church's first vicar.  The stained glass in the east window is also to the first vicar's memory and is dated 1875.  There is a window in the south chancel wall dated 1877, and windows in the north chancel wall dated 1914 and 1920.<ref name=int>{{Citation | url = http://www.stgeorgechorley.co.uk/interior.html| title = Interior| accessdate = 13&nbsp;December 2011| publisher = The Parish Church of St George, Chorley}}</ref>  The glass in the west window is by Stephen Adam, and depicts the [[Resurrection of Jesus|Resurrection]].<ref name=pev/>  The [[chandelier]]s were installed in 1977, having previously been in [[St Mary's Church, Ulverston]].  The clock in the tower was installed in 1920.<ref name=int/>  The three-[[manual (music)|manual]] organ was made in about 1870 by Kirtland and Jardine, with modifications by E.&nbsp;Walklet in 1934.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.npor.org.uk/cgi-bin/Rsearch.cgi?Fn=Rsearch&rec_index=N01668| title = Lancashire, Chorley, St. George (N01668)| accessdate = 13&nbsp;December 2011| publisher = [[British Institute of Organ Studies]]}}</ref>  The bells consists of an [[Ellacombe apparatus|Ellacombe]] [[Chime (bell instrument)|Chime]], made by Mears and Stainbank at the [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]], and installed in 1919.<ref name=int/>

